SAMPLE TRAUMA 1):

CLINICAL REPORT

MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING OF THE RIGHT SHOULDER I.

CLINIC: Trauma.
TECHNIQUE:
Examination performed on magnetic resonance equipment, with multiplanar sequences and specific weights for the
segment of interest, without the administration of paramagnetic contrast medium.

RESULT:: Acromion type II. Degenerative changes in the acromioclavicular joint, with edema at the end of the clavicle.
Glenohumeral joint without significant changes. Small glenohumeral joint effusion. Liquid distension of the subacromiodeltoid
bursa. Glenoid labrum with no detectable changes. Thickening and heterogeneous signal of the supraspinatus and infraspinatus
tendons, due to tendinopathy. Complete rupture of the supraspinatus and infraspinatus tendons, near the insertion, with tendon retraction being observed at a distance of about 2.7 cm from the large humeral tuberosity. Thickening and heterogeneous sign of the subscapularis tendon, due to tendinopathy. Smaller Redondo tendon of preserved thickness and signal. Tendon of the long
portion of the biceps thickened in its intra-articular portion, due to tendinopathy. Volumetric reduction of the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscle bellies, as well as of the minor round. Other muscle groups with normal thickness and signal
characteristics. Free rotator interval and axillary recess. Edema in the deep adipose planes.

CONCLUSION: Degenerative changes in the acromioclavicular joint, with edema at the end of the clavicle. Small
glenohumeral joint effusion and liquid distension of the subacromiodeltoid bursa. Thickening and heterogeneous signal of the
supraspinatus and infraspinatus tendons, due to tendinopathy. Complete rupture of the supraspinatus and infraspinatus tendons, near the insertion, with distant tendon retraction observed. Thickening and heterogeneous sign of the subscapularis tendon, due to tendinopathy. Tendon of the long portion of the biceps thickened in its intra-articular portion, due to tendinopathy. Volumetric reduction of the supraspinatus and infraspinatus muscle bellies, as well as of the minor round. Edema in the deep adipose planes.

SAMPLE TRAUMA 2):

CLINICAL REPORT

COMPUTED TOMOGRAPHY OF THE LEFT SHOULDER
CLINIC: Trauma.
TECHNIQUE:
Examination performed on a computed tomography device, with collimation, filters and specific reconstructions for the segment of interest, without intravenous administration of contrast medium.

RESULT: Comminuted fracture of the humeral head, with anterior dislocation. Moderate hemarthrosis. Thickening and densification of the deltoid muscle belly and also densification of the subcutaneous tissue in the anterior portion, related to trauma.

CONCLUSION:
Comminuted fracture of the left humeral head, with anterior and moderate dislocation in hemarthrosis.

SAMPLE WITHOUT TRAUMA

CLINICAL REPORT

MAGNETIC RESONANCE IMAGING OF THE RIGHT SHOULDER I.

CLINIC: Without trauma.
TECHNIQUE:
Examination performed on magnetic resonance imaging equipment with specific sequences, weights, and plans for the segment of interest, without intravenous administration of the contrast medium

RESULT:: Acromioclavicular arthrosis, characterized by marginal osteophytes and small subcortical cysts and bone edema at the ends of the acromion and clavicle, in addition to minor joint effusion. Vascular cysts/remnants in the humeral head. Partial rupture of the middle and upper articular fibers of the subscapular tendon, measuring about 1.6 cm, with a retraction of about 2.0 cm of the tendon stump, compromising about 50% of the tendon thickness. Supraspinal and infra-spinal tendinopathy, especially partial intrassubstantial rupture in the rear supraspinal fibers and superior infraspinal fibers measuring approximately 1.2 x 1.0 cm, affecting less than 50% of the tendon thickness, with degenerative subcortical cysts and bone edema in the humeral head. Thickening of the subacromial/subdeltoid bursa. Mild hypotrophy and liporeplacement of the subscapular and infraspinal muscle ventri. Smaller round tendon with preserved thickness, continuity, and signal. Long cable tendon of the biceps brachialis centered on the biceps sulcus, preserved in the intra- and extra-articular pathways. Glenoidal lip structures with regular contours and preserved signal, without injury. Absence of glenohumeral joint effusion

CONCLUSION: Acromioclavicular arthrosis. Partial rupture of the middle and upper articular fibers of the subscapular tendon. Supraspinal and infra-spinal tendinopathy, with special intrassubstantial partial rupture in the rear supraspinal and superior infraspinal fibers. Signs of subacromial/ subdeltoid bursitis. Mild hypotrophy and liporeplacement of the subscapular and infraspinal muscle ventri.
